{"title_page": "David Rudder", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = David Rudder\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = David Michael Rudder\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|5|6}}\n| death_date          = \n| origin              = Belmont, [[Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar\n| genre               = [[Calypso music|Calypso]], [[soca music|soca]]\n| occupation          = Musician, singer, producer, song-writer\n| years_active        = 1977\u2013present\n| label               = [[Sire Records|Sire]]/[[Warner Bros. Records]] (1986\u201390)\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = [http://www.davidmichaelrudder.com/ www.davidmichaelrudder.com]\n}}\n'''David Michael Rudder''' (born 6 May 1953) is a Trinidadian [[calypsonian]], known to be one of the most successful calypsonians of all time. \nHe performed as lead singer for the brass band Charlie's Roots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/charlies-roots-mn0000773484|title=Charlie's Roots - Biography & History|website=AllMusic|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> Nine years later, Rudder stepped outside the band, entering the Calypso Tent as a solo calypsonian in 1986, which was followed by an unprecedented rise to fame.<ref name=\"davidmichaelrudder.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.davidmichaelrudder.com/Biography.php|title=David Rudder Biography Achievements & Awards|website=www.davidmichaelrudder.com|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"Almost overnight he became a national hero on the order of [[Bob Marley|Marley]] in Jamaica, [[Fela]] in Nigeria and [[Springsteen]] in New Jersey,\" wrote Daisann McClane, American journalist and [[Worldbeat]] correspondent for ''[[Rolling Stone Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caribbean-beat.com/issue-9/david-rudder-breakthrough|title=David Rudder: The Breakthrough|first=Debbie |last=Jacob |issue= 9|date=1 January 1994|magazine=[[Caribbean Beat Magazine]]|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis music quickly became the subject of music critics around the world. \"From New York to London to Tokyo, where the Japanese have released a CD of Rudder's greatest hits complete with lyrics translated into Japanese, Rudder has been described as modern calypso's most innovative songwriter.\"<ref name=\"davidmichaelrudder.com\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Belmont, Trinidad and Tobago|Belmont, Port of Spain]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], one of nine children, Rudder spent much of his early life with his grandmother, a devout Baptist.<ref name=AllMusic>Craig Harris, [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/david-rudder-mn0000811508/biography \"Artist Biography\"], [[AllMusic]].</ref> He began singing with a calypso band at a young age, and in his teens sang backup vocals in a calypso tent run by [[Lord Kitchener (calypsonian)|Lord Kitchener]],<ref name=AllMusic /> while earning his living as an accountant with the Trinidad Bus Company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.panonthenet.com/tnt/2019/tunes/el.htm|title=EL (Ellie) - 2019 Pan Tunes - Steelband Panorama - David Rudder - Carnival 2019|website=When Steel Talks/PanOnTheNet|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, he joined [[Charlie's Roots]], a leading band in Trinidad and Tobago, which launched with help and sponsorship from New York-based record producer Rawlson Charles,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/neo/NeoProxy.dll?app=NeoDirect&com=6/2/349600/fb57bb26de|title=Roots to share|first=David|last=Cuffy|website=www.guardian.co.tt|date=7 January 2016|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> and Rudder spent many years as one of the band's vocalists.\n\nIn 1986, he came to prominence on [[Andy Narell]]'s album ''The Hammer'', which produced two big hits: \"The Hammer\" (a tribute to the late [[steelpan|pannist]] [[Rudolph Charles]]) and \"Bahia Girl\". This was followed in 1987 with \"Calypso Music\", a brilliant encapsulation of the history of [[Calypso music|calypso]]. In 1988 Rudder released what is widely considered his best album to date, ''Haiti'', which included the [[Haiti I Am Sorry|title track]], a tribute to the glory and suffering of [[Haiti]];<ref>[http://www.panonthenet.com/news/2010/jan/haiti.htm \"\u2018Haiti\u2019 sung by David Rudder\"], When Steel Talks, 2008.</ref> \"Engine Room\", which captured the energy of the steel band; and \"Rally 'Round the West Indies\",<ref>{{youtube|x-MgkoLKMr0|David Rudder - Rally Round The West Indies}}</ref> which became the anthem of [[West Indian cricket team|West Indies cricket]].\n\nIn 1991, four tracks performed by Rudder were included in the soundtrack of the film ''[[Wild Orchid (film)|Wild Orchid]]'': \"Dark Secret\" (two versions), \"Children Of Fire (Call Of Xango)\", and \"Just a Carnival\", which includes Rudder in the final scene in the movie \"performing\" on the beach. In 2008, Rudder did a [[Soca music|Soca]] collaboration with fellow Trinidadian [[Machel Montano]], \"Oil and Music\" on Machel's 2007 album ''[[Flame On]]''. In 2011 David Rudder performed a soca collaboration called \"Glow\" with Barbados' Queen of Soca [[Alison Hinds]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yRoXn3Osumo \"Alison Hinds ft. David Rudder - Glow\".]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Album\n!colspan=\"4\"|Peak positions\n|-\n!align=\"center\" width=\"60\"|<small>[[Billboard 200|U.S. top 200]]</small>\n!align=\"center\" width=\"60\"|<small>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2001\n|align=\"left\"| ''The Autobiography of the Now''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2000\n|align=\"left\"| ''Zero''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"| ''International Chantuelle''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"| ''Beloved''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1996\n|align=\"left\"| ''Wrapped in Plain Brown Paper''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1995\n|align=\"left\"| ''Tales from a Strange Land''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1995\n|align=\"left\"| ''Gilded Collection\u2014Volume 1''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1994\n|align=\"left\"| ''Lyrics Man''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1993\n|align=\"left\"| ''Here Comes the West Indies''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1990\n|align=\"left\"| ''1990''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1987\n|align=\"left\"| ''Haiti'' (with Charlie's Roots)\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidmichaelrudder.com David Rudder's] official website\n* [https://www.myspace.com/davidruddermusic David Rudder's] official MySpace Page\n* Joy A. I. Mahabir, [https://web.archive.org/web/20050312131310/http://social.chass.ncsu.edu/jouvert/v613/mahabi.htm \"Rhythm and Class Struggle: The Calypsoes of David Rudder\"], ''Jouvert'' 6 (3), 2002.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rudder, David}}\n[[Category:Calypsonians]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Trinidad and Tobago descent]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sire Records artists]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Port of Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = David Rudder\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = David Michael Rudder\n| alias               = \n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1953|5|6}}\n| death_date                = \n| origin              = Belmont, [[Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar\n| genre               = [[Calypso music|Calypso]], [[soca music|soca]]\n| occupation          = Musician, singer, producer, song-writer\n| years_active        = 1977\u2013present\n| label               = [[Sire Records|Sire]]/[[Warner Bros. Records]] (1986\u201390)\n| associated_acts     = \n| website                 = [http://www.davidmichaelrudder.com/ www.davidmichaelrudder.com]\n}}\n'''David Michael Rudder''' (born 6 May 1953) is a Trinidadian [[calypsonian]], known to be one of the most successful calypsonians of all time. \nHe performed as lead singer for the brass band Charlie's Roots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/charlies-roots-mn0000773484|title=Charlie's Roots - Biography & History|website=AllMusic|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> Nine years later, Rudder stepped outside the band, entering the Calypso Tent as a solo calypsonian in 1986, which was followed by an unprecedented rise to fame.<ref name=\"davidmichaelrudder.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.davidmichaelrudder.com/Biography.php|title=David Rudder Biography Achievements & Awards|website=www.davidmichaelrudder.com|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"Almost overnight he became a national hero on the order of [[Bob Marley|Marley]] in Jamaica, [[Fela]] in Nigeria and [[Springsteen]] in New Jersey,\" wrote Daisann McClane, American journalist and [[Worldbeat]] correspondent for ''[[Rolling Stone Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caribbean-beat.com/issue-9/david-rudder-breakthrough|title=David Rudder: The Breakthrough|first=Debbie |last=Jacob |issue= 9|date=1 January 1994|magazine=[[Caribbean Beat Magazine]]|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis music quickly became the subject of music critics around the world. \"From New York to London to Tokyo, where the Japanese have released a CD of Rudder's greatest hits complete with lyrics translated into Japanese, Rudder has been described as modern calypso's most innovative songwriter.\"<ref name=\"davidmichaelrudder.com\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Belmont, Trinidad and Tobago|Belmont, Port of Spain]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], one of nine children, Rudder spent much of his early life with his grandmother, a devout Baptist.<ref name=AllMusic>Craig Harris, [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/david-rudder-mn0000811508/biography \"Artist Biography\"], [[AllMusic]].</ref> He began singing with a calypso band at a young age, and in his teens sang backup vocals in a calypso tent run by [[Lord Kitchener (calypsonian)|Lord Kitchener]],<ref name=AllMusic /> while earning his living as an accountant with the Trinidad Bus Company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.panonthenet.com/tnt/2019/tunes/el.htm|title=EL (Ellie) - 2019 Pan Tunes - Steelband Panorama - David Rudder - Carnival 2019|website=When Steel Talks/PanOnTheNet|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, he joined [[Charlie's Roots]], a leading band in Trinidad and Tobago, which launched with help and sponsorship from New York-based record producer Rawlson Charles,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.tt/neo/NeoProxy.dll?app=NeoDirect&com=6/2/349600/fb57bb26de|title=Roots to share|first=David|last=Cuffy|website=www.guardian.co.tt|date=7 January 2016|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> and Rudder spent many years as one of the band's vocalists.\n\nIn 1986, he came to prominence on [[Andy Narell]]'s album ''The Hammer'', which produced two big hits: \"The Hammer\" (a tribute to the late [[steelpan|pannist]] [[Rudolph Charles]]) and \"Bahia Girl\". This was followed in 1987 with \"Calypso Music\", a brilliant encapsulation of the history of [[Calypso music|calypso]]. In 1988 Rudder released what is widely considered his best album to date, ''Haiti'', which included the [[Haiti I Am Sorry|title track]], a tribute to the glory and suffering of [[Haiti]];<ref>[http://www.panonthenet.com/news/2010/jan/haiti.htm \"\u2018Haiti\u2019 sung by David Rudder\"], When Steel Talks, 2008.</ref> \"Engine Room\", which captured the energy of the steel band; and \"Rally 'Round the West Indies\",<ref>{{youtube|x-MgkoLKMr0|David Rudder - Rally Round The West Indies}}</ref> which became the anthem of [[West Indian cricket team|West Indies cricket]].\n\nIn 1991, four tracks performed by Rudder were included in the soundtrack of the film ''[[Wild Orchid (film)|Wild Orchid]]'': \"Dark Secret\" (two versions), \"Children Of Fire (Call Of Xango)\", and \"Just a Carnival\", which includes Rudder in the final scene in the movie \"performing\" on the beach. In 2008, Rudder did a [[Soca music|Soca]] collaboration with fellow Trinidadian [[Machel Montano]], \"Oil and Music\" on Machel's 2007 album ''[[Flame On]]'' . In 2011 David Rudder  performed a soca collaboration called \"Glow\" with Barbados' Queen of Soca [[Alison Hinds]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yRoXn3Osumo \"Alison Hinds ft. David Rudder - Glow\".]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Album\n!colspan=\"4\"|Peak positions\n|-\n!align=\"center\" width=\"60\"|<small>[[Billboard 200|U.S. top 200]]</small>\n!align=\"center\" width=\"60\"|<small>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</small>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2001\n|align=\"left\"| ''The Autobiography of the Now''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2000\n|align=\"left\"| ''Zero''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"| ''International Chantuelle''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"| ''Beloved''\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|