 \n| music8 = \n| extra8 = [[Trans-Siberian Orchestra]]\n| length8 = 4:59\n| title9 = Reindeer\n| note9 = Dialogue\n| writer9 = \n| lyrics9 = \n| music9 = \n| extra9 = \n| length9 = 0:35\n| title10 = Christmas Is Going to the Dogs\n| writer10 = [[Mark Oliver Everett]]\n| lyrics10 = \n| music10 = \n| extra10 = [[Eels (band)|Eels]]\n| length10 = 2:57\n| title11 = [[You're a Mean One, Mr. Grinch]]\n| writer11 = Seuss, Hague\n| lyrics11 = \n| music11 = \n| extra11 = Carrey\n| length11 = 2:31\n| title12 = Christmas Means More\n| note12 = Dialogue\n| writer12 = \n| lyrics12 = \n| music12 = \n| extra12 = \n| length12 = 0:49\n| title13 = You Don't Have to Be Alone (On Christmas)\n| writer13 = [[JC Chasez]], Veit Renn and David Nicoll\n| lyrics13 = \n| music13 = \n| extra13 = [['N Sync|*NSYNC]]\n| length13 = 4:33\n| title14 = [[Where Are You, Christmas?]]\n| writer14 = Horner, [[Will Jennings]] and [[Mariah Carey]]\n| lyrics14 = \n| music14 = \n| extra14 = [[Faith Hill]]\n| length14 = 4:07\n| title15 = The Shape of Things to Come\n| note15 = \n| writer15 = \n| lyrics15 = \n| music15 = \n| extra15 = \n| length15 = 6:31\n| title16 = Memories of a Green Childhood\n| note16 = \n| writer16 = \n| lyrics16 = \n| music16 = \n| extra16 = \n| length16 = 3:28\n| title17 = [[Christmas, Why Can't I Find You?]]\n| writer17 = Horner, Jennings\n| lyrics17 = \n| music17 = \n| extra17 = [[Taylor Momsen]]\n| length17 = 2:09\n| title18 = Stealing Christmas\n| note18 = \n| writer18 = \n| lyrics18 = \n| music18 = \n| extra18 = \n| length18 = 6:55\n| title19 = The Big Heist\n| note19 = \n| writer19 = \n| lyrics19 = \n| music19 = \n| extra19 = \n| length19 = 4:01\n| title20 = Does Cindy Lou Really Ruin Christmas?\n| note20 = \n| writer20 = \n| lyrics20 = \n| music20 = \n| extra20 = \n| length20 = 4:10\n| title21 = A Change of Heart\n| note21 = \n| writer21 = \n| lyrics21 = \n| music21 = \n| extra21 = \n| length21 = 3:44\n| title22 = The Sleigh of Presents\n| note22 = \n| writer22 = \n| lyrics22 = \n| music22 = \n| extra22 = \n| length22 = 6:01\n| title23 = He Carves the Roast Beast\n| note23 = \n| writer23 = \n| lyrics23 = \n| music23 = \n| extra23 = \n| length23 = 3:10\n}}\n\n==Release==\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[VHS]] and [[DVD]] on November 20, 2001.<ref>{{cite web| first=John| last=Jimenez| url=http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/product_article.cfm?article_id=1124| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010620000327/http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/product_article.cfm?article_id=1124| title=Universal to \u2018Turn World Green\u2019 for \u2018Grinch\u2019| website=[[Hive4media.com]]| archivedate=June 20, 2001| date=April 26, 2001| accessdate=September 8, 2019| url-status=live}}</ref> A [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]]/DVD combo pack was released on October 13, 2009. In December 2001, ''Variety'' reported that it was the second biggest selling home video release of 2001, selling 16.9 million copies and earning $296 million in sales revenue.<ref>{{cite news| title=Year End 2001 Top-selling overall| url=https://variety.com/2001/biz/news/year-end-2001-top-selling-overall-627028/| date=December 30, 2001| newspaper=Variety| accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref> It was also remastered in 4K Ultra HD.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''How the Grinch Stole Christmas'' grossed $260 million domestically and $85.1 million in other territories for a worldwide gross of $345.1 million, becoming the sixth highest-grossing film of 2000.\n\nIn the United States, ''The Grinch'' opened at number-one on its opening day, making $15.6 million, with a weekend gross of $55.0 million, for an average of $17,615 from 3,127 theaters. The film held the record for the highest opening weekend for a Christmas-themed film for 18 years until the 2018 film version of ''The Grinch'' passed it with $67.6 million. In its second weekend, the film grossed $52.1 million, dropping only 5.1%, settling a new record for [[List of highest-grossing second weekends for films|highest-grossing second weekend]] for any film at the time. The film stayed at the top of the box office for four weekends until it was overtaken by ''[[What Women Want]]'' in mid-December. The film closed on April 30, 2001, after five months with a final gross of $260,044,825.<ref name =\"BOM\"/> [[Box Office Mojo]] estimates that the film sold over 48.1 million tickets in North America.<ref>{{cite web| access-date=November 11, 2018| url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=grinch.htm&adjust_yr=1&p=.htm| title=How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000)| website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 51% based on 140 reviews, with an average rating of 5.52/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Jim Carrey shines as the Grinch. Unfortunately, it's not enough to save this movie. You'd be better off watching the [[Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas! (TV special)|TV cartoon]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/how_the_grinch_stole_christmas/|title=How the Grinch Stole Christmas|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 46 out of 100, based on 29 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/how-the-grinch-stole-christmas|title=How the Grinch Stole Christmas|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/| title=Find CinemaScore| work=[[CinemaScore]]| access-date=November 11, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/| archive-date=December 20, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film two out of four stars, referring to it as \"a dank, eerie, weird movie about a sour creature\" and said, \"There should be&nbsp;... a jollier production design and a brighter look overall&nbsp;... It's just not much fun.\" Ebert observed that Carrey \"works as hard as an actor has ever worked in a movie, to small avail\". Nevertheless, he decided that \"adults may appreciate Carrey's remarkable performance in an intellectual sort of way and give him points for what was obviously a supreme effort\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20001117/REVIEWS/11170303| title=''Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas''| via=rogerebert.com| newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]| date=November 17, 2000| author-link=Roger Ebert| first=Roger| last=Ebert| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Paul Clinton]] of [[CNN]] declared that Carrey \"was born to play this role\" and noted that \"Carrey carries nearly every scene. In fact, if he's not in the scene, there is no scene.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2000/SHOWBIZ/Movies/11/17/review.grinch/index.html| title=Review: Steal away to see the latest 'Grinch'| work=[[CNN]]| date=November 17, 2000| first=Paul| last=Clinton| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' began his review of the film analyzing the Grinch's \"mischievously divided, now-I'm-calm/ now-I'm-a-raving-sarcastic-PSYCH-o! personality\" and summed up Carrey's Grinch as \"a slobby, self-loathing elitist ruled by the secret fear that he's always being left out of things.\" Gleiberman expressed surprise at \"how affecting Carrey makes the Grinch's ultimate big-hearted turnaround, as Carrey the actor sneaks up on Carrey the wild-man dervish. In whichever mode, he carreys {{sic}} the movie.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=https://ew.com/article/2000/11/24/how-grinch-stole-christmas/|title=''How the Grinch Stole Christmas'' Review| work=Entertainment Weekly| date=November 24, 2000| first=Owen| last=Gleiberman| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPeter Stack of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' said, \"Nobody could play the Grinch better than Jim Carrey, whose rubbery antics and maniacal sense of mischief are so well suited to ''How the Grinch Stole Christmas''. Dr. Seuss himself might have turned to Carrey as a model for the classic curmudgeon had the actor been around in 1957.\" However, he wondered why Carrey \"made himself sound like [[Sean Connery]]\" and warned that the character's intensity may frighten small children.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/How-Effects-Stole-Christmas-Supercharged-3302567.php| title=How Effects Stole 'Christmas' / Supercharged 'Grinch' stays true to Seuss but amps up Carrey's character| work=San Francisco Chronicle| date=November 17, 2000| first=Peter| last=Stack| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] of ReelViews wrote that Carrey's \"off-the-wall performance is reminiscent of what he accomplished in ''The Mask'', except that here he never allows the special effects to upstage him. Carrey's Grinch is a combination of Seuss' creation and Carrey's personality, with a voice that sounds far more like a weird amalgamation of Sean Connery and [[Jim Backus]] ([[James Bond|Bond]] meets [[Mr. Magoo|Magoo]]!) than it does [[Boris Karloff|Karloff]].\" He concluded that Carrey \"brings animation to the live action, and, surrounded by glittering, fantastical sets and computer-spun special effects, Carrey enables Ron Howard's version of the classic story to come across as more of a welcome endeavor than a pointless re-tread.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/h/how_grinch.html| title=Reelviews Movie Reviews| journal=ReelViews| date=November 17, 2000| first=James| last=Berardinelli| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome reviews were more polarized. [[Stephanie Zacharek]] of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' in a generally negative review of the film, wrote that \"Carrey pulls off an admirable impersonation of an animated figure ... It's fine as mimicry goes&nbsp;\u2013 but mimicry isn't the best playground for comic genius. Shouldn't we be asking more of a man who's very likely the most gifted comic actor of his generation?\" She concluded that in spite of \"a few terrific ad-libs&nbsp;... his jokes come off as nothing more than a desperate effort to inject some offbeat humor into an otherwise numbingly unhip, nonsensical and just plain dull story\".<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.salon.com/2000/11/17/grinch/| title=''Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas''| journal=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]| date=November 17, 2000| first=Stephanie| last=Zacharek| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote, \"Carrey tries out all sorts of intonations, vocal pitches and delivery styles, his tough guy posturing reminding at times of [[James Cagney|Cagney]] and his sibilant S's recalling [[Humphrey Bogart|Bogart]]. His antic gesturing and face-making hit the mark at times, but at other moments seem arbitrary and scattershot. Furthermore, his free-flowing tirades, full of catch-all allusions and references, are pitched for adult appreciation and look destined to sail right over the heads of pre-teens.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/dr-seuss-how-the-grinch-stole-christmas-1200465392/| title=''Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas''| magazine=Variety| date=November 16, 2000| first=Todd| last=McCarthy| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup]]\n| [[Rick Baker]] and [[Gail Ryan|Gail Rowell-Ryan]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]]\n| [[Michael Corenblith]] and [[Merideth Boswell]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n| [[Rita Ryack]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| [[Jim Carrey]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Awards]]\n| [[Kids' Choice Award for Favorite Movie|Favorite Movie]]\n| \n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Favorite Movie Actor \n| rowspan=\"2\" | Jim Carrey\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Awards]]\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Best Villain|Best Villain]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-off or Sequel|Worst Remake or Sequel]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]]\n| [[Jeffrey Price and Peter S. Seaman]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Film|Best Fantasy Film]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Ron Howard]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Jim Carrey\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Performance by a Younger Actor|Best Performance by a Younger Actor]]\n| [[Taylor Momsen]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Costume|Best Costume]]\n| Rita Ryack, David Page\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Music|Best Music]]\n| [[James Horner]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Make-Up|Best Make-Up]]\n| Rick Baker and Gail Rowell-Ryan\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|United States|Christianity}}\n* [[Grinch]]\n* [[The Grinch (film)|''The Grinch'' (film)]]\n* [[The Grinch (video game)|''The Grinch'' (video game)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas (film)|Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas}}\n{{commons category|Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas}}\n* {{IMDb title|0170016}}\n* {{tcmdb title|546845}}\n* {{Mojo title|grinch}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|how_the_grinch_stole_christmas}}\n* {{Metacritic film|how-the-grinch-stole-christmas}}\n\n{{Dr. Seuss}}\n{{Grinch}}\n{{Ron Howard}}\n{{Brian Grazer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s Christmas films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about orphans]]\n[[Category:Films about bullying]]\n[[Category:Films based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Dr. Seuss]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ron Howard]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Ron Howard]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Brian Grazer]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jeffrey Price and Peter S. Seaman]]\n[[Category:Films scored by James Horner]]\n[[Category:Films set in fictional populated places]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles County]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Utah]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Academy Award for Best Makeup]]\n[[Category:Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:Imagine Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 2000 live-action film known as \"The Grinch\" in the UK|the 2018 computer animated film|The Grinch (film)}}\n{{short description|2000 film by Ron Howard}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = How the Grinch Stole Christmas\n| image          = How the Grinch Stole Christmas film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ron Howard]]\n| producers      = [[Brian Grazer]]<br />Ron Howard\n| screenplay     = [[Jeffrey Price and Peter S. Seaman|Jeffrey Price <br />Peter S. Seaman]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[How the Grinch Stole Christmas!]]''|[[Dr. Seuss]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|<!--PER POSTER BILLING-->\n* [[Jim Carrey]]\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]]\n* [[Christine Baranski]]\n* [[Bill Irwin]]\n* [[Molly Shannon]]\n}}\n| narrator       = [[Anthony Hopkins]]\n| music          = [[James Horner]]\n| cinematography = [[Donald Peterman|Don Peterman]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Daniel P. Hanley|Dan Hanley]]\n* [[Mike Hill (film editor)|Mike Hill]]\n}}\n| studio         = [[Imagine Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2000|11|08|[[Los Angeles]]|2000|11|17|United States}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes<ref name=\"bbfc\">{{cite web| title=The Grinch| url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/grinch-film| website=[[British Board of Film Classification]]| language=en}}</ref><br />\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $123 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web| url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=grinch.htm| title=How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000)| website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $345.1 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n'''''How the Grinch Stole Christmas''''' (also known as '''''Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas''''' and simply '''''The Grinch''''' in the UK) is a 2000 American [[Christmas film|Christmas]] [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Ron Howard]] and written by [[Jeffrey Price and Peter S. Seaman]]. Based on [[Dr. Seuss]]'s [[How the Grinch Stole Christmas!|1957 book of the same name]], it was the first Dr. Seuss book to be adapted into a full-length feature film. The film is narrated by [[Anthony Hopkins]] and stars [[Jim Carrey]] in the [[Grinch|title role]] along with [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Christine Baranski]], [[Bill Irwin]] and [[Molly Shannon]] in supporting roles, as well as introducing [[Taylor Momsen]] as Cindy Lou Who.\n\nBecause the film is based on a children's picture book, many additions were made to the storyline in order to bring it up to feature-length, including some information about the backstory of the title character and reworking the story's minor character Cindy Lou Who as a main character. Most of the rhymes that were used in the book were also used in the film, though some of the lines were to some degree changed and several new rhymes were put in. The film also borrowed some music and character elements that originated in the [[How the Grinch Stole Christmas! (TV special)|1966 animated television special]], such as the song \"[[You're a Mean One, Mr. Grinch]]\" and the Grinch's green skin tone.\n\nProduced by Howard and [[Brian Grazer]]'s [[Imagine Entertainment]], ''How the Grinch Stole Christmas!'' was released by [[Universal Pictures]] in the United States on November 17 and received mixed reviews from critics who criticized the screenplay, characters and innuendos but praised the musical score, Carrey\u2019s performance and production values. The film grossed over $345 million worldwide, becoming the [[2000 in film|sixth-highest grossing film of 2000]] and was originally the second highest-grossing holiday film of all-time behind ''[[Home Alone]]'' (1990), until both films were surpassed in 2018 by the [[The Grinch (film)|third film adaptation of the story]].<ref name=\"BOM\"/><ref>{{cite book| title=Guinness World Records 2007| url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec2007guin|url-access=registration| publisher=Guinness World Records Limited| year=2006| page=[https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec2007guin/page/n197 182] (UK edition)| chapter=Arts & Media| isbn=978-1-9049-9412-1}}</ref> It won the [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Academy Award for Best Makeup]] as well as getting nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]] and [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please refer to WP:FILMPLOT before editing. Plots for films should be between 400-700 words. Also see [[User:NinjaRobotPirate/How to streamline a plot summary]] for excellent tips. -->\nAll the residents of [[Whoville]] (Whos) enjoy celebrating [[Christmas]]. The [[Grinch]], a misanthropic and devious green-furred creature, arrives in Whoville as a baby and was adopted by two elderly sisters. He was a timid child who had a crush on Martha May Whovier, one of the prettiest girls in his school, who showed empathy towards him. Bully Augustus May Who, however, was jealous that Martha liked the Grinch more than him and began to mock him for having a beard. Because of this, the Grinch cut his face while attempting to shave, to which his classmates \u2014 except Martha \u2014 laughed at him and caused the Grinch to lose his temper and declare that he hates Christmas. He fled to the top of Mount Crumpit, north of Whoville, for which he lived there.\n\n53 years later, nobody likes the Grinch due to the harmful stunts he pulls on them. Meanwhile, six-year-old Cindy Lou Who believes that everyone is missing the point about Christmas by focusing too much on the gifts and festivities and too little on the personal relationships. She then has a face-to-face encounter with the Grinch at the post office and later discovers his tragic past.\n\nCindy nominates the Grinch to be the town's \"Holiday Cheermeister\", much to the displeasure of May Who, who is now the mayor of Whoville. Cindy climbs to Mount Crumpit to invite the Grinch to the celebration and he eventually accepts. As Cheermeister, the Grinch participates in several events and begins to have fun, but May Who reminds him of his childhood humiliation by giving him an electric shaver as a present before publicly proposing marriage to Martha and giving her a gaudy engagement ring. Enraged, the Grinch berates the Whos for their materialism by telling them that Christmas is only about gifts that they will end up throwing in the garbage, which is dumped on Mount Crumpit near his home. He destroys the tree and goes on a rampage around Whoville, before going back home to Mt. Crumpit.\n\nFinally fed up with the Whos' Christmas, the Grinch concocts a plan to crush the Whos' Christmas spirit by stealing all of their presents, decorations and food while they're sleeping. He disguises himself as [[Santa Claus]] and dresses his dog Max as a [[reindeer]], then descends into Whoville. The first house he enters is Cindy's, and lies to Cindy when she catches him stealing their tree, allowing him to escape. The Grinch continues stealing all of the gifts, decorations and food and stuffing them all in a large sack, before climbing back to the top of Mt. Crumpit to destroy the gifts by pushing the sack off the side. When the Whos wake up on Christmas morning, they are horrified to discover the theft and May Who blames Cindy for letting this happen to Whoville. However, her cheerful father, town postmaster Lou Lou Who, comes to his daughter's defense by explaining to Maywho and all of the other Whos that he has finally figured out what Cindy has been trying to tell the whole town \u2014 Christmas is mainly about love of family and friends, not just gifts and fancy lights. The Whos agree with Lou and start singing Whoville's Christmas carol.\n\nBefore the Grinch can push the stolen gifts off the top of Mount Crumpit, he hears the Whos singing and realizes that he has failed to prevent Christmas, but then has an epiphany and finally realizes the true meaning of Christmas, causing his heart to grow three sizes. The sleigh full of gifts begins to slide over the edge of the cliff along with Cindy, who had come to spend Christmas with him. The Grinch gets the strength to lift the loaded sleigh and carry Cindy to safety, and they ride down the mountain to return the gifts.\n\nThe Grinch apologizes for the burglary and surrenders himself to the police, who accept his apology and deny May Who's request to arrest and [[pepper spray]] the Grinch. Martha even turns down May Who's proposal and returns his engagement ring to him, declaring that her heart belongs to the Grinch. Afterwards, the redeemed Grinch joins in the Whos' celebration feast and carves the roast beast himself in his cave.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jim Carrey]] as [[the Grinch]], a misanthropic and devious green-furred creature who despises Christmas and the Whos of Whoville. It is revealed in his origin story that he started to hate Christmas after his school classmates mocked him for trying to shave his face. Before Carrey was cast to play the Grinch, [[Jack Nicholson]]<ref name=\"SeussontheLoose\">{{cite news| last=Cagle| first=Jess| \nurl=http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,87540,00.html| title=Seuss on the Loose| work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]| date=November 11, 2000| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> and [[Eddie Murphy]]<ref>{{cite web| last=Evans| first=Bradford| title=The Lost Roles of Eddie Murphy| date=7 April 2011| journal=[[Splitsider]]| url=http://splitsider.com/2011/04/the-lost-roles-of-eddie-murphy/| accessdate=18 July 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723072044/http://splitsider.com/2011/04/the-lost-roles-of-eddie-murphy/| archive-date=July 23, 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref> were briefly considered.\n** [[Josh Ryan Evans]] as the 8-year-old Grinch; his humiliation at school by May Who is what drives him into a hatred of Christmas. This was Evans' last film role before he died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2002-aug-07-me-evans7-story.html|title=Joshua Evans, 20; 3-Foot, 2-Inch Actor Starred in TV's 'Passions'|date=2002-08-07|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n* Kelley as Max, the Grinch's pet dog and only companion on Mt. Crumpit. It is unknown how and when the Grinch got him.\n**[[Frank Welker]] voices Max.\n\n* [[Christine Baranski]] as Martha May Whovier, the Grinch's lifelong crush, the kindest citizen of Whoville and the romantic interest of Mayor May Who. In the end, she ultimately rejects the Mayor and chooses the Grinch.\n** Landry Allbright as 8-year-old Martha May Whovier. She shows compassion towards the young Grinch.\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]] as Mayor Augustus May Who, Whoville's rude, arrogant and judgmental mayor. He is revealed to be a school bully who picked on the young Grinch over his shaved face, which is what motivated the Grinch to hate Christmas in the first place. He also denounces the Grinch every chance he gets and wants Christmas in Whoville to be Grinch-less.\n** Ben Bookbinder as 8-year-old Augustus May Who; he tormented the young Grinch, which motivated the Grinch to hate Christmas.\n* [[Taylor Momsen]] as Cindy Lou Who, a young Who girl who believes that the Christmas spirit in Whoville is lost. In the film, she is 6 years old whereas in the book in 1957 and the TV special in 1966 she is \"no more than 2\".\n* [[Bill Irwin]] as Lou Lou Who, the cheerful and slightly dimwitted postmaster of Whoville, as well as Cindy's father.\n* [[Molly Shannon]] as Betty Lou Who, Cindy's mother and Martha's rival in a house-lighting contest.\n* [[Clint Howard]] as Whobris, the mayor's sycophantic aide and servant. He goes along with everything the Mayor says and does.\n** Reid Kirchenbauer as 8-year-old Whobris. \n* [[Mindy Sterling]] as Clarnella Who, one of the Grinch's adoptive mothers in his childhood.\n* Rachel Winfree as Rose Who, one of the Grinch's adoptive mothers in his childhood.\n* [[Jeremy Howard (actor)|Jeremy Howard]] as Drew Lou Who, one of the troublesome sons of Lou and Betty and brothers of Cindy.\n* [[T. J. Thyne]] as Stu Lou Who, one of the troublesome sons of Lou and Betty and brothers of Cindy.\n* [[Jim Meskimen]] as Officer Wholihan, the chief of police.\n* [[Mary Stein]] as Miss Rue Who, the Grinch's school teacher who later becomes Cindy's teacher.\n* [[Deep Roy]] as Post Office [[Clerk]]\n* [[Rance Howard]] as Elderly [[Timekeeper]]\n* [[Verne Troyer]] as Band Member\n* [[Bryce Dallas Howard]] as Surprised Who\n* [[Ron Howard]] as Whoville Townperson (uncredited)\n*[[Anthony Hopkins]] as the Narrator\n\n== Production ==\n[[File:Ron Howard 2011 Shankbone 3.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Ron Howard]] is the film's director and producer.]]\nBefore his death in 1991, [[Dr. Seuss]] had refused offers to sell the film rights to his books. However, his widow Audrey Geisel, agreed to several merchandising deals, including clothing lines, accessories and CDs.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/652411/Universal-purchases-rights-for-2-Dr-Seuss-characters.html| title=Universal purchases rights for 2 Dr. Seuss characters| newspaper=[[Deseret News]]| date=September 17, 1998| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> In July 1998, Geisel's agents announced via letter she would auction the film rights of ''How the Grinch Stole Christmas''. In order to pitch their ideas to Geisel, the suitors ultimately had to be willing to pay $5 million for the material and hand over 4 percent of the box-office gross, 50 percent of the merchandising revenue and music-related material, and 70 percent of the income from book tie-ins. The letter also stated that \"any actor submitted for the Grinch must be of comparable stature to Jack Nicholson, Jim Carrey, [[Robin Williams]] and [[Dustin Hoffman]].\" Additionally, it was stipulated that the estate would not consider a director or writer who had not earned at least $1 million on a previous picture.<ref name=\"SeussontheLoose\"/>\n\n[[20th Century Fox]] pitched its version with director [[Tom Shadyac]] and producers Dave Phillips and [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]] in attendance, in which Jack Nicholson was in mind to play the Grinch.<ref>{{cite magazine| url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/carrey-plays-grinch/| title=Carrey Plays The Grinch| magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]| date=September 17, 1998| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> Additionally, the [[Farrelly brothers]] and [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]] pitched their own separate versions.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.newsweek.com/grinchs-gatekeeper-156985| title=The Grinch's Gatekeeper| work=[[Newsweek]]| date=November 11, 2000| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> [[Universal Pictures]] held its pitch presentation with Brian Grazer and [[Gary Ross]] in attendance, but Geisel refused such offer. Grazer then enlisted his producing partner Ron Howard to help with the negotiations. At the time, Howard was developing a film adaptation of ''[[The Sea-Wolf]]'', and, despite being an avid fan of the animated special, did not express interest in ''Grinch'', but Grazer talked Howard into traveling to Geisel's residence for the pitch meeting.<ref>{{cite news| last=Head| first=Steve| url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/11/07/dr-seuss-widow-objected-to-elements-in-early-scripts-for-the-grinch| title=Dr. Seuss' Widow Objected To Elements In Early Scripts for the Grinch| website=[[IGN]] News| date=November 7, 2000| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> While studying the book, Howard became interested in the character Cindy Lou Who and pitched a film in which she would have a larger role as well as a materialistic representation of the Whos and an expanded backstory of the Grinch.<ref name=\"SeussontheLoose\"/><ref>{{cite news| last=Scribner |first=Sarah| url=http://articles.courant.com/2000-11-17/features/0011170882_1_audrey-geisel-grinch-doctor-dr-seuss| title=Grinch Doctor| newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]]| date=November 11, 2000| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, 1998, it was announced that Howard would direct and co-produce a live-action adaptation of ''How the Grinch Stole Christmas'' with Jim Carrey attached to star.<ref>{{cite magazine| last=Fleming| first=Michael| url=https://variety.com/1998/film/news/u-imagine-clinch-grinch-pic-deal-1117480452/|title=U, Imagine clinch \u2018Grinch\u2019 pic deal |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]| date=September 16, 1998| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> It was also reported that Universal Pictures, who had acquired the distribution rights, paid $9 million for the film rights for an adaptation of ''Grinch'' and ''[[Oh, the Places You'll Go!]]'' to Geisel.<ref>{{cite news| last=Eller| first=Claudia| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/sep/16/business/fi-23114| title=Seuss Rights Sold for Up to $9 Million| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]| date=September 16, 1998| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> [[Jeffrey Price and Peter S. Seaman]] (of both ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'' and ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' fame) wrote the final screenplay following eight drafts, but Geisel also had veto power over the script. She objected to several jokes and sexual innuendos in the screenplay, including one about a family who did not have a Christmas tree or presents jokingly called the \"Who-steins\" and the placement of a stuffed trophy of [[the Cat in the Hat]] on the Grinch's wall.<ref>{{cite news| last=Armstrong| first=Mark| title=Mrs. Seuss: Whoville Is Not Poo-ville| url=https://www.eonline.com/news/40708/mrs-seuss-whoville-is-not-poo-ville |journal=[[E! News]]| date=November 6, 2000| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> [[Alec Berg]], [[David Mandel]] and [[Jeff Schaffer]] (who were also writers on the television series ''[[Seinfeld]]'') did an uncredited rewrite of the script.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/dec/04/entertainment/ca-credits4|title=Credit ascribed, denied| last1=Horn| first1=John| last2=Abramowitz| first2=Rachel| date=December 4, 2005| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film was shot between September 1999 and January 2000. Geisel visited the set in October 1999. Much of the Whoville set was constructed on the backlot of [[Universal Studios Hollywood|Universal Studios]] behind the Bates Motel set from ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''. [[Rick Baker]] was hired to design and create the film's prosthetic makeup for Carrey and the rest of the cast. It took a number of tests, and ultimately Carrey admiring a photo of Baker in his first test makeup, for the decision to use Baker's original makeup design. The Grinch suit was covered in yak hair, dyed green and sewed onto a spandex suit. The application of the makeup took up to 2 and a half hours, after which a frustrated Carrey kicked a hole in the wall of his trailer. Carrey's makeup artist [[Kazuhiro Tsuji]] took the most from Carrey's anger. \"On set, [Carrey] was really mean to everybody and at the beginning of the production they couldn't finish,\" Tsuji said. \"After two weeks we only could finish three days' worth of shooting schedule, because suddenly he would just disappear and when he came back, everything was ripped apart. We couldn't shoot anything.\" Tsuji left production until Baker had a discussion with Carrey on how important Tsuji was to the production. Carrey agreed to keep his anger in check and Tsuji returned to his role.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Nate|date=December 1, 2017|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/12/kazuhiro-tsuji-gary-oldman-darkest-hour.html|title=How Gary Oldman Lured a Makeup Magician Back for One More Job|work=Vulture|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, Josh Ryan Evans, who played the 8-year old Grinch, wore the same makeup and bodysuit that Carrey wore. In total, Carrey spent 92 days in the Grinch make-up, and became adept at remaining calm while sitting in the make-up chair. Most of the appliances the actors wore were noses that connected to an upper lip along with a few dentures, ears and wigs.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack for the album was released on November 7th, 2000.<ref>{{cite web| title=How the Grinch Stole Christmas Soundtrack 2000 Film| url=https://www.amazon.com/How-Grinch-Stole-Christmas-Soundtrack/dp/B000050HSZ| website=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]| accessdate=2019-11-18}}</ref> It features a collection of music from popular artists of the time, as well as dialogue segments from the film.{{Infobox album\n| name         = Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = Various artists\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2000|11|7}}\n| recorded     = 2000\n| genre        = * [[Christmas music|Christmas]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n* [[Film score|film score]]\n| length       = 73:19\n| label        = *[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\nAll song lengths via [[Apple Music]].<ref>{{Citation| title=Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) by James Horner| url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/dr-seuss-how-grinch-stole-christmas-original-motion/1440913794| language=en-us| access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>{{Track listing\n| headline = \n| extra_column = Performed by\n| total_length = \n| all_writing = \n| all_lyrics = \n| all_music = [[James Horner]], except where noted\n| title_width = \n| writing_width = \n| music_width = \n| lyrics_width = \n| extra_width = \n| title1 = Kids Today\n| note1 = Dialogue\n| writer1 = \n| lyrics1 = \n| music1 = \n| extra1 = \n| length1 = 0:21\n| title2 = Grinch 2000\n| writer2 = [[Dr. Seuss]] and [[Albert Hague]]\n| lyrics2 = \n| music2 = \n| extra2 = [[Busta Rhymes]] and Jim Carrey\n| length2 = 3:34\n| title3 = [[Green Christmas (song)|Green Christmas]]\n| writer3 = [[Steven Page]] and [[Ed Robertson]]\n| lyrics3 = \n| music3 = \n| extra3 = [[Barenaked Ladies]]\n| length3 = 2:35\n| title4 = Christmas of Love\n| writer4 = [[Rick Chertoff]], David Forman a